    <annotation>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Mult&ugrave;m valet Leo: sed Leo, et Vulpes, mult&ograve; plus.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The lion is very strong: but the lion and the fox are stronger.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Omnes res perinde sunt, vt agas, ut eas magni facias. Spiritus int&ugrave;s alit.
                    Ca[e]sar, iudicio fortis, et inuictus.</marginalia_text>
                    <X-ref person="Plautus" book_title="Comedies"/> <!--Also appears in Cicero's 'De Oratore'.-->
                    <X-ref person="Virgil" book_title="Aeneid"/> <!--book VI, 726-->
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>"All things are just as you may perform them, as you may consider them important." [Glazebrook et al. (eds), 2011, 185].
            "The spirit nourishes within." Caesar, brave and invincible in judgement.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="90">
                    <marginalia_text>Vehementissimi oratores: sic ipse Dauid: sic Vlysses: sic omnes, instructi heroica fortitudine
                    , aut Eloquentia. Diuinus furor, et numen.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="King David"/>
                    <person name="Odysseus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The most vigorous orators: thus David himself, thus Odysseus. Thus all instructed with heroic valor or eloquence.
            Divine rage and will.</translation>
        </marginalia> 
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Camillus furius. Papyrius Cursor.
                    In vno Ca[e]sar, multi Marij. Vim Alexandri, potissim&ugrave;m a[e]mulabatur Ca[e]sar: Vim Demostenis, Cineas.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Marcus Furius Camillus"/>
                    <person name="Lucius Papirius Cursor"/>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                    <person name="Gaius Marius"/> <!--JG: Not entirely sure-->
                    <person name="Alexander the Great"/>
                    <person name="Demosthenes"/>
                    <person name="Cineas"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Marcus Furius Camillus. Lucius Papirius Cursor. 
                Caesar in one,  many of the Marius. <!--JG: Not entirely sure-->
                Caesar was jealous of the most powerful strenght of Alexander; Cinaes [was jealous of] the strenght of Demosthenes.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
                    <marginalia_text>Tam in Agendo, qu&agrave;m in Dicendo, semper acris vehementia excelluit, et fulmineus vigor:
                    Achilles, Alexander, Ca[e]sar, vehementissimi Actors: Pericles, Demosthenes, Cineas</marginalia_text> 
                    <person name="Achilles"/>
                    <person name="Alexander the Great"/>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                    <person name="Pericles"/>
                    <person name="Demosthenes"/>
                    <person name="Cineas"/>
                </position>
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Sylla, pla[e]risque foelix; Ceceroni vehemens; vt etiam Ca[e]sar acer. (Nemo admod&ugrave;m foelix, nisi idem vehemens, et acer.) </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Sulla"/>
                    <person name="Cicero"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>In doing as well as in speaking, sharp eagerness and destructive vigor always excell.
            Achilles, Alexander, Caesar, most vehement actors: Perciles, Demosthenes, Cineas, Sulla, generally successful. <!--JG: Unsure, need to get back to translation-->
            Severe to Cicero; while even Caesar [was] sharp (No one was exceedingly successful, unless similarly vehement and sharp).</translation>
        </marginalia> 
        
